Is there any hope that this Detroit Red Wings team can turn it around in the second half and make a run at a playoff berth? 
 
Full disclosure, I don’t work for the Red Wings. I never have worked for the Red Wings. And odds are that I never will work for the Red Wings. 
 
The only reason that I mention it is that I think the 25-year playoff streak matters a lot to the people who work inside the organization. I don’t think that those of us who work outside the organization appreciate what it means to those people. This isn’t an excuse, it’s more of an explanation. For years, simply making the playoffs was a foregone conclusion for the Red Wings. It was merely a matter of where they’d be seeded and who they’d host in Game 1 of the first round. The last few years, it’s been a matter of scratching and clawing their way in and sometimes relying on other teams losing to secure that final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. 
 
This hasn’t led to any postseason success. It clearly hasn’t led to any deep runs in the spring. But as Ken Holland likes to infer, once you’re in, anything can happen. The only problem is that “anything” has been a series of first round losses with only one playoff round victory (2013) in the past five seasons and zero trips to the conference finals since 2009. 
 
It’s led to a weird dynamic in this town where the team is fighting to get in and the fans are saying, “what’s the point?” 
 
